Current Issue













Greenberg out as CEO of MMC




Reprints



Gavin Souter


10/25/2004 12:00:00 AM


Share

Facebook
LinkedIn
Google +
Twitter


Agents & Brokers
Marsh & McLennan
More +
Less -





NEW YORK--Jeffrey W. Greenberg has resigned as chairman and chief executive officer of embattled brokerage Marsh & McLennan Cos. Inc., the company announced after the stock market closed Monday.The announcement comes less than two weeks after New York Attorney General Eliot Spitzer sued MMC, charging it with fraudulent self-dealing and bid-rigging through its use of contingent commission arrangements.Mr. Greenberg will be replaced by Michael G. Cherkasky, the former CEO of MMC's Marsh Kroll consulting unit, who, soon after Mr. Sptizer's suit was filed, was named head of Marsh Inc., MMC's brokerage unit.New York-based MMC also announced in a statement that on Tuesday it will announce "significant reforms in the business model" of Marsh, which "will be rooted in transparency and under which Marsh will receive compensation for its services from only one party: its clients."MMC also announced that it had appointed a special committee of outside directors "to spearhead the company's activities in resolving its legal and regulatory matters," the statement notes. The committee will be headed by Robert F. Erburu, former chairman of The Times Mirror Co.Mr. Greenberg joined Marsh & McLennan as a senior executive at its investment arm in 1995, a few months after he stunned the insurance industry by leaving American International Group Inc. Mr. Greenberg had been seen as the heir apparent to his father, AIG Chairman and CEO Maurice R. Greenberg.Jeffrey W. Greenberg was then named president of MMC in January 1999, and later that year he took on the additional role of CEO. He became chairman on the retirement of A.J.C. Smith in May 2000.As head of the holding company, Jeffrey W. Greenberg was responsible for overseeing the three main business units of MMC: the insurance brokerage unit, Marsh; the benefits consulting unit, Mercer Inc.; and its investment unit, Putnam Investments Inc.Last year, Putnam was the subject of regulatory and civil suits accusing it of improper trading practices. In April this year, Putnam agreed to pay $110 million to settle the charges with regulators and replaced longtime Putnam CEO Lawrence Lasser.




















